Klotz refers to Bottiger’s Sabina to show

that these extravagant dames of antiquity could spend the income of a whole com- munity 011 such ornaments as Cicero al- ludes to. This may be so 3 but it seems more reasonable to consider that these do- nations were made nominally for such and such purpose, not because a woman re- quired the revenue of a whole district to keep her hair or head-gear in order. When Artaxerxes provided royally for the traitor Themistocles (Thucyd. i. 138), by giving him Magnesia as bread, Lampsacus as wine, and so forth, the Greek made something of his bread, for it amounted to fifty talents the year, rather more than he and his household would consume.
